clude nearby elements.","score":0.63234437,"raw_content":null},{"url":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61785743/how-to-animate-backdrop-filter","title":"css - How to animate backdrop-filter? - Stack Overflow","content":"### your communities. ### more stack exchange communities. Communities for your favorite technologies. Stack Overflow for Teams is now called **Stack Internal**. ##### Collectives™ on Stack Overflow. # How to animate backdrop-filter? I faced the issue with low fps while using backdrop-filter and transition on the same component. The animation is glitchy :( But if I comment out backdrop-filter line, things are getting better. You can achieve a different but comparable effect by instead animating the `backdrop-filter`'s `opacity()` like so:. backdrop-filter: blur(4px) opacity(0);. But on the plus side, I've also found this approach to be much more performant than the alternative suggestion of animating a (non-backdrop) `filter` property's `blur()`. I believe, it's a very new property and can't be animated properly yet. If you are trying to apply a backdrop on modal, don't. Thanks for contributing an answer to Stack Overflow! Find the answer to your question by asking. ##### Stack Overflow. ##### Stack Exchange Network.","score":0.5158888,"raw_content":null},{"url":"https://css-tricks.com/using-css-backdrop-filter-for-ui-effects/","title":"Using CSS backdrop-filter for UI Effects | CSS-Tricks","content":"# Using CSS backdrop-filter for UI Effects. You’ll learn how to layer *backdrop filters* among multiple elements, and integrate them with other CSS graphical effects to create elaborate designs. The difference between the CSS `filter` and `backdrop-filter` properties is the affected part of an element. *Backdrop filter* affects the backdrop of an element, and it requires a transparent or translucent background in the element for its effect to be visible. ### Layering elements with backdrop filters. ### Combining backdrop filters with other CSS effec